<HEADLINE>
<P>
COOK IT LIGHT: VICHYSSOISE: HOW TO CUT CALORIES, BOTHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNE JONES, Jones is a food consultant and a cookbook author. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vichyssoise is a rich, creamy potato soup that is always served cold. Like many 
famous French dishes, it actually started out as a way to use up leftovers -- 
in this case, leftover leek-and-potato soup. 
</P>
<P>
The soup was combined with heavy cream and served cold so that it became 
totally unrecognizable as a leftover. 
</P>
<P>
My lighter version of this classic is much easier to make than the original 
French technique. It also has a fraction of the calories and cholesterol per 
serving. 
</P>
<P>
For formal dinner parties I like to serve Vichyssoise in icers garnished with a 
dollop of caviar. For less formal buffet gatherings I sometimes serve the soup 
in mugs before seating my guests for dinner. 
</P>
<P>
VICHYSSOISE WITH CAVIAR 
</P>
<P>
2 medium baking potatoes (1 pound), peeled and diced 
</P>
<P>
2 cups chopped white onions 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 cups defatted chicken stock 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup nonfat milk 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup light sour cream 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon salt (omit if using salted stock) 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons freshly squeezed lemon juice 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup minced onion 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup caviar 
</P>
<P>
Combine potatoes and onions in large saucepan. Add chicken stock and bring to 
boil. Reduce heat and simmer, covered, until potatos are tender, about 20 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Spoon cooked potato mixture into blender container or food processor. Add 
nonfat milk, sour cream, salt and lemon juice. Cover and chill well. 
</P>
<P>
To serve, pour 1/2 cup cold soup into each of 8 chilled bowls. Top each serving 
with 1 tablespoon minced onion and 1/2 tablespoon caviar. Makes 8 (1/2-cup) 
servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains approximately 80 calories; 54 mg cholesterol; 4 g fat; 
300 mg sodium. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recipe; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081690-0029 </DOCNO>
