<P>
SAN DIGEO COUNTY DIGEST: FALLBROOK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite the efforts of more than 50 firefighters, a historic fruit-packing 
plant in Fallbrook was gutted early Wednesday morning, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old, 154,000-square-foot Lemon Twist plant, originally known as the 
Fallbrook Citrus Plant, was destroyed, said North County Fire Protection 
District dispatcher Greg Holdridge. Citrus fruits were still being packed at 
the plant. 
</P>
<P>
One firefighter suffered a broken ankle while fighting the blaze, which 
apparently began about 1:30 a.m. No other injuries were reported, Holdridge 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Damage to the building, in the 200 block of West College Street, was estimated 
at $1.5 million, Holdridge said. 
