<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: CONNER SYNDICATE ADDS NEW SPONSOR, DESIGNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dennis Conner's America's Cup defense campaign announced Wednesday that it had 
secured Pepsi-Cola as a major sponsor for the effort. 
</P>
<P>
Pepsi was a founding corporate sponsor when Conner won the America's Cup back 
from Australia in 1987 and defended it against New Zealand in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
A press release from "Team Dennis Conner" said Pepsi's sponsorship had allowed 
the syndicate to begin building the first of three International America's Cup 
Class boats it is planning and that it hopes to have it ready next spring. 
</P>
<P>
Conner also announced that Alberto Calderon, a physicist who helped develop the 
innovative "twin wing" concept used by the 12-meter USA in 1987, would be 
joining the design team of David Pedrick. 
</P>
<P>
Peter Debreceny, executive director for New Zealander Michael Fay's America's 
Cup challenges in Fremantle, Australia, and San Diego, has joined the Beach 
Boys USA Syndicate as marketing adviser, the syndicate announced. 
</P>
<P>
HOCKEY 
</P>
<P>
The Gulls, San Diego's new International Hockey League franchise, announced the 
signing of two players, defenseman Pete Dineen and forward Carl Mokosak. 
</P>
<P>
Dineen, 29, will be in his 10th season of professional hockey, including time 
with the NHL's Los Angeles Kings in 1986 and the Detroit Red Wings last year. 
</P>
<P>
Mokosak entered pro hockey in 1981 with the Calgary Flames and also has spent 
time in Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh and Boston. He played with Fort 
Wayne and Phoenix of the IHL last year, with 18 goals, 27 assists and 363 
minutes in penalties in 70 games. 
</P>
<P>
The Gulls now have three players, including Charlie Simmer, a player/assistant 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
BODY SURFING 
</P>
<P>
The 14th world championships will be held at the Oceanside Pier Friday through 
Sunday beginning each morning at 6:30. Approximately 400 body surfers will 
compete in eight men's and three women's categories. 
</P>
<P>
BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
Palomar College announced it had hired Richard Johnson, a Gardner-Webb (N.C.) 
College assistant, as its basketball coach. He succeeds Andy Gilmour, who 
resigned after 21 years. Johnson, 39, had a 217-38-1 record in 10 seasons as a 
Georgia high school coach, then coached part-time at the University of Georgia 
for three years before becoming an assistant at Gardner-Webb last season. As a 
player, he led the nation in community college rebounding in 1971. 
</P>
</TEXT>
