<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
TAIWAN TARIFF CUT ON 1,900 ITEMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TAIPEI, Taiwan 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tariffs will be reduced on 1,900 goods in a market-widening move designed to 
support Taiwan's bid to join the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the 
Finance Ministry said today. 
</P>
<P>
A ministry section chief said the government is drafting a list of about 1,900 
imported products, including passenger cars, automobile components, farm goods 
and precision instruments, that could have their import tariffs cut early next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of our tariff cut is to encourage imports and liberalize our 
market," the official said in a telephone interview. "It is also in line with 
our plans to join GATT." 
</P>
<P>
Taiwan had a trade surplus of $12 billion with the United States in 1989, 
although the figure is expected to drop below $10 billion this year, Taiwan 
trade officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
