<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
BRITISH WAGES, JOBLESSNESS UP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Average earnings of British workers rose 10% in the year ending in June despite 
government appeals to employers to hold down wage costs to fight high 
inflation, official figures showed today. 
</P>
<P>
In another blow to the Conservative government, which is trailing the 
opposition Labor Party in opinion polls, unemployment increased by a seasonally 
adjusted 10,900 in July to 1.63 million or 5.7% of the work force. 
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth consecutive month for lengthened unemployment lines in 
Britain. 
</P>
<P>
Both earnings, up from 9.75% in May, and the increase in unemployment were 
above market expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
